##Breathing heavily during an outbreak | in hopes of giving the baby a better future

Micro Signal Xiezuozheyunshegong

FUNCTION INTRODUCTION: Volunteer Information Management, social worker information management, public welfare information release, social work professional exchange

This article is one of the case interviews conducted by the collaborators in the "Peasant Workers' anti-epidemic Rescue Action" , aiming at quickly identifying the vulnerable groups and their needs in the epidemic situation, and providing reference for the epidemic prevention, control and rescue work, we put it together and share it with you.

Deep breathing in case of an outbreak
A case study on the families of migrant workers in distress in Foshan (8)

I want to give my child a better future
Narrator: Ursula Gauthier (not his real name) , Shandong native
Place of employment: Qingdao

Editor's Note: Ursula Gauthier, a 44 year old migrant worker from Shandong province, has no schooling and comes from a family of five. Ursula Gauthier, who has lived in Qingdao for more than 10 years, now lives near South Korea and China in the Mount Lao district of Qingdao. He has a headache and takes painkillers every day when he is severe. The father works part-time. Although not very well off, Ursula Gauthier believes that children are content with a good education when they can go to school in the city.

I hope the children can receive a good education

I was born in the eldest daughter, a family came to Qingdao, there are more than 10 years, during the second daughter, the third daughter was born in Qingdao. The eldest daughter has gone to college and is doing an internship in a shopping mall. The second daughter is in the fifth grade and the third daughter is in the first grade. The reason why I chose to stay in the city at the beginning was that I didn't go to school. The school conditions in the city are good. I hope my children can receive a good education and have a better future.

Co-author social workers learn about life at home (photo taken in October 2019)

The father's health is OK, I have a headache problem, strong to take medicine will be better. Because he was afraid to go to the hospital to check out other problems, so headache went to the pharmacy to get pain medication, 18 yuan a box of about 20 tablets, when the headache is serious to eat.
No contracts, no social security

Because I did not go to school, do not know how to read, changed the work quite a lot. Last year, my friend introduced me to a job that paid about 2,800 yuan a month for bathing babies and toddlers. I've been doing it ever since, but I have no contract and no social security. The father works part-time, the income also is not fixed, good time a month more than 6000 yuan, also did not have to oneself to insure the social insurance. My husband and I had only the new rural cooperative medical scheme in our old village. We knew a little about the other commercial insurance, but we couldn't afford it. Including children, only the school and the home of the new rural cooperative insurance, other commercial insurance is not.
It was only when there were fewer and fewer people in the mall that the severity of the outbreak became apparent

My family has an old van, the General New Year is the second day of driving back, because of the epidemic, this year did not go home for the New Year. We knew about the outbreak on January 20, but that day parents seemed to give their children more baths and didn't care. Then on January 21, suddenly there were fewer people in the mall, and on January 22, there were fewer people in the whole mall, and almost no one, to get a sense of the severity of the epidemic. I follow the news of the epidemic on my mobile phone, although I can't read, but I feel this is very important, I will often watch the progress of the epidemic on my mobile phone.
As long as the children can be fed and fed, they will feel at ease

Now I live in the village has closed the village, the village has no related epidemic propaganda, no temperature measurement, there is no hair mask, the village is surrounded by iron, only give out not to let in. January 27(the third day of the first month) when you can also enter and exit registration, is now an ID card are not allowed to enter. All we can do now is stay at home and keep away from people. Let the children eat more, drink more water, wash their hands frequently, go out must wear a mask.

The Guo Yu family's rental house (photo taken in May 2019)

I also experienced SARS, then has been in Qingdao, the current situation is similar to SARS, but also some tension, but not very severe. The only difference is that SARS as long as there are documents can be normal access to live in the place, now this epidemic is not to allow access, the feeling is trapped in the home, some do not adapt.

I personally feel that this epidemic will last 1-2 months, the impact on life will be very big, the current home of rice and flour surplus is not much, eat for three or five days is not a problem. The village market is also closed, dare not go out, the village only let out not to let in, worried about out after what to do. Under normal circumstances in previous years, outsiders have gone, the village market to buy supplies is also a problem.

The past ten days, now finally a little better, the village has a place to buy food. The basic basic needs of the family can be met, but the main concern is the financial source. At present, we have no income, and we live on the money we don't have to go home for the New Year. If we can't, we need to borrow some from our sister, the adults said they couldn't let the kids suffer. I hope the epidemic will be over soon so I can go to work and earn money.

If this epidemic continues for three or six months, I hope to get support and help in life, as long as the children can eat and drink enough, feel at ease, not so nervous.

Social Worker's notes

The illiterate Ursula Gauthier, who had experienced SARS during her time as a migrant worker, is now experiencing a new outbreak of pneumonia, so in today's call, she feels less scared about the outbreak and more concerned about the impact on her life, especially that of her children. The security of the people comes from the smooth flow of food, clothing, shelter and transportation. In the face of severe epidemic prevention and control, Ursula Gauthier still harbors hope. Although she has not studied for a day, she knows the importance of education. Therefore, even if life is difficult, she still wants the baby to be okay!
Service advice
Now:
1. COVID-19;
2. Provide basic relief supplies, face masks and disinfection supplies;
3. In order to follow up the situation of the village closure, if necessary, to assist in the purchase of living goods.
LONG-TERM:
11. Promote knowledge of social security and Labour Contract Law of the People's Republic of China;
2. Providing employment counselling to broaden the scope of employment options;
3: Continue to provide financial aid.
